column85: Pt took his own life and it begs the question of whether the pt didn't have enough support, if DBS made things worse, or if it was depression from the medication.

column37: DTI data acquired 2x before surgery, 1st time likely postponed 9/26/16 (Ax. 11198189).
column85:
1/5/17 pt sometimes takes Sinemet 1/2 tab every 2hrs if dyskinesias severe (not inlcuded in LEDD score).
2/22/17 pt takes Sinemet 100mg PRN in between Rytary doses (not included in LEDD score).
4/11/17 pt stopped taking her Sinemet 4 days ago because her dyskinesias were bothersome. Being off the sinemet has helped with the dyskinesias.
4/21/17 neurologist advised pt to restart her sinemet 25/100, 1/2 tab 3-4 times/day and increase it if necessary.
9/21/17 pt stopped taking Amantadine 1-2 months ago, but has not noticed any worsening in dyskinesias or other symptoms. 
8/15/18 pt tried 1/2 tab of Sinemet, but this gave her a throbbing headaches and became more dyskinetic in the evening.

column37:
**CHECK WITH MELANIE ON WHAT POSTOP IMAGES TO USE??
R-electrode, lead extension and pulse generator removed, likely infection based on MRI. Postop only includes L-electrode (+ all left hardare still in). 
Using postop T1 imaging instead of immediate postop CT imaging after R side hardware removed due to a 4cm cyst around the right DBS lead.
column85:
7/12/17 pt is no longer taking Amantadine. He is now only taking Carbidopa/Levodopa 50/200 CR one tablet at 7AM and possibly one in the afternoon. He only needs immediate release C/L occasionally. 
11/29/17 pt has been taking Sinemet CR at 7AM and 1PM. Benefit wears off after about 3-4 hours characterized by freezing of gait and balance difficulties. He occasionally takes Sinemet CR at 6PM, especially before jiu jitsu, but he often forgets. 
11/7/18 pt has been unable to increase his Sinemet dose. He does not " feel right" when he takes it - even though it helps his movements-, and he develops dyskinesias with a low dose, for which he takes Amantadine, which helps but makes him feel mentally "foggy".

5/2/18 pt weaned off the Pramipexole as advised over 2 months, and he also dropped one of his 2 doses of Amantadine about one month ago. 
5/6/20 pt continues to take Sinemet and has adjusted his timing slightly, but overall same daily amount (1000-1200mg levodopa).
10/28/20 pt stopped taking Sinemet CR at bedtime 2 weeks ago because it made him restless and he sleeps much better taking an Advil PM instead. He continues Sinemet 3 tabs Q3H with minimal wearing-off unless he didn't sleep well the night before. His last dose of Sinemet is ~3pm and wears off slightly in the evenings but it's mild and not bothersome to him -- walking slows and he feels cognitively slower, but he's usually relaxing at home during these times. If there is a social activity he will take an extra 1/2-1 tab of Sinemet in the evenings prior to it. 
6/2/21 pt tried restarting his Sinemet CR at bedtime and he noticed some improvement in his symptoms the first night, but then the second night he experienced the same restlessness so stopped that again. 
8/25/21 At his last visit, it was recommended that he increased his dose to 3 more tablets at 6PM to help on evening off symptoms.

8/24/18 when pt reduced Rytary to 2 caps QID she had more difficulty with fine motor control in the hands and perceived that she had more difficulties with multitasking, so she increased to 4 caps QID.
11/26/18 pt has reduced Requip to 1/2 tab QID. Overall, she reports no definite and obvious motor worsening. Trying to wean pt off Requip all together.

column84: Patient feeling 70% on during ON testing.
column85:
8/13/18 Since surgery, the pt has been able to eliminate the two daytime doses of sinemet CR he had been taking.
1/28/19 neurologist suggested that the pt try reducing the dose of his bedtime Rytary from 3 capsules to 2 capsules (9:30 pm dose) to help with the hallucinations. 
4/1/19 pt was back up to Rytary 195 mg 3 caps 5x daily (with DBS off). At this dose, he was verbalizing delusions much more. He has since decreased Rytary to 2 195 mg caps 5x daily. He feels that he had more ON time with a single dose cycle and overall had better movement at 3 caps 5 x daily. However, with reduction to 2 caps, the auditory hallucinations decreased and he verbalized his delusions less.

8/13/18 Since surgery, the pt has been able to eliminate the two daytime doses of sinemet CR he had been taking.
1/28/19 neurologist suggested that the pt try reducing the dose of his bedtime Rytary from 3 capsules to 2 capsules (9:30 pm dose) to help with the hallucinations. 
4/1/19 pt was back up to Rytary 195 mg 3 caps 5x daily (with DBS off). At this dose, he was verbalizing delusions much more. He has since decreased Rytary to 2 195 mg caps 5x daily. He feels that he had more ON time with a single dose cycle and overall had better movement at 3 caps 5 x daily. However, with reduction to 2 caps, the auditory hallucinations decreased and he verbalized his delusions less.

column85:

9/2/20 left foot dystonia in the morning has resolved with adding 1/2 tab of Sinemet IR at 3am.

column85:

column37: Has 'bone recon' postop CT.
column85:
1/16/19 pt reports that she titrated down her Mirapex due to feeling as though it impaired her balance. She is now taking 1/2 of a 0.75mg tablet three times daily, and thinks that her balance is much better as a result. She is interested in decreasing even further.
6/26/19 pt described cramping in her toes with the toes flexing at times on the right more than the left foot. This gets better after her medications. It may represent and off medication dystonia and has been happening more since taking a lower strength Rytary tablet 145mg compared to the 195mg tab she ran out of.
1/29/20 pt had increased her carbidopa/levodopa to 2 tabs 5x/day as was recommended by Dr. Ostrem but she felt that it was too much. She reports feeling extremely tense on the higher dose and felt her body twisting more to the left. She is having difficulty deciding if she is taking too much or too little carb/levo. She decreased her mirapex on her own. Four days ago, she started breaking her mirapex 0.25 mg in 1/2 and is now taking 1/2 tab 3x/day.
3/4/20 the pt's mood has been down recently. She is not sure if related to cutting down Mirapex.

12/19/18 pt tried to reduce Rytary by 95mg each dose but could not tolerate this.
5/17/19 At his last appointment last month, pt was doing well and we decided to try to reduce the dose of Rytary. This seems to have triggered residual impaired sleep and recurrence of severe anxiety and depression. Motor symptoms are much worse in the off-medication state. His hands are cold and toes are "numb" and this is likely an off-medication symptom. Insomnia is worse on the lower dose of Rytary, there's a lot of anxiety at night, sleep maintenance is the main issue. Confusion is worse in the setting of all of this. He went back to close to the prior dose of Rytary but for some reason he is only taking it QID instead of 5 times per day. He will return to the full prior dose.
7/12/19 non-motor off symptoms resolved going back to the prior higher Rytary dose.

6/3/20 Since DBS, pt has had significant improvement in his motor symptoms, especially tremors, and is requiring less Rytary. He is now taking Rytary 195, 3 caps BID to TID, rather than 5-6x daily as he was prior to DBS. He still takes Sinemet IR 25/100 mg PRN on average about once daily to every other day. 7/27/20 patient stopped taking all PD medication.  She previously had a trial of Sinemet, but was unable to tolerate Sinemet due to nausea and stopped taking it on her own.
2/22/21 pt increased sinemet to 1.5 tabs TID and she is not sure this has helped tremor any more than before. 
3/4/21 pt increased Sinemet to 2 / 2 / 1.5 and she is tolerating it well - she thinks it is helping slightly more. She has not had falls since increasing the sinemet. 
5/24/21 pt increased Sinemet to 2 tabs TID but unfortunately had no improvement in involuntary rubbing of her left heel early in the morning. Pt feels that tremor is worse, particularly in left hand, but also in right hand. She is having more memory difficulties - word finding troubles in particular. Lastly, she resumed amantadine at 100 mg BID in the interim and noted no additional benefit to tremor.
9/28/21 pt has increased Sinemet to 2.5 / 2.5 / 2 to better target L hand tremor.

11/19/20 pt has moved his Rytary to 5 95mg capsules TID and finds that these doses mostly last until the next dose, with occasional wearing off in between.
12/10/20 pt  has been taking Rytary 4 caps TID, reduced from 5 capsules TID. He tried decreasing to 3 capsules TID, which felt better for him, but we discussed a slower wean would be beneficial.
1/21/21 decreased Rytary 23.75/95mg from 4 to 3 tabs TID given improving motor sx, persistent dyskinesias, and sense of feeling "hyperactive." Hyperactivity has improved with decreasing Rytary dose. 
5/27/21 pt tried to reduce the 5pm Rytary to 2pills and found he just didn't have enough energy to continue on that dose. He still has intermittent dyskinesias around dinner time, which is about 1hour after his 5pm Rytary dose. 
7/29/21 pt was able to decrease his first AM dose to 2 caps but also added a dose at 9:30 AM because he was "running out of gas" before noon, which has been helpful. Occasionally, he takes 3 caps at 6 PM. With 3 caps, he develops dyskinesias in the head/neck. These are mostly noted by his wife but sometimes bothersome to the patient.

12/10/20 pt  has been taking Rytary 4 caps TID, reduced from 5 capsules TID. He tried decreasing to 3 capsules TID, which felt better for him, but we discussed a slower wean would be beneficial.
1/21/21 decreased Rytary 23.75/95mg from 4 to 3 tabs TID given improving motor sx, persistent dyskinesias, and sense of feeling "hyperactive." Hyperactivity has improved with decreasing Rytary dose. 
5/27/21 pt tried to reduce the 5pm Rytary to 2pills and found he just didn't have enough energy to continue on that dose. He still has intermittent dyskinesias around dinner time, which is about 1hour after his 5pm Rytary dose. 
7/29/21 pt was able to decrease his first AM dose to 2 caps but also added a dose at 9:30 AM because he was "running out of gas" before noon, which has been helpful. Occasionally, he takes 3 caps at 6 PM. With 3 caps, he develops dyskinesias in the head/neck. These are mostly noted by his wife but sometimes bothersome to the patient.

column85:
11/5/20 further adjustment to the pt's  Rytary to QID has pretty much eliminated off time and dyskinesias have not been problematic.
6/9/22 pt currently taking 3 capsules of Rytary 245 mg QID every 4 hours, but it's only lasting about 2.5-3 hours (even after taking Comtan with each dose).
10/13/22 since DBS surgery, motor symptoms have continued to progress and he has required higher and more frequent doses of Rytary for symptom control.

column37: Has 'bone recon' postop CT.
column85:
10/20/22 pt saw local neurologist recently, recommended switching from previous regimen of Rytary + Sinemet to just Sinemet more often because of feeling off intermittently. 
Has felt like his balance has been a bit off as well as some L toe curling, but hasn't had any falls. Perhaps some benefit with increased dose. No worsening dyskinesais. 
12/8/22 pt has worsened speech/mumbling and possibly could be a synergistic effect with Levodopa, so will try to decrease Levodopa.
4/19/23 pt stopped the Ropinirole on advice of local neurologist recently.

column85:
3/24/22 pre-op meds were 3 tabs Q3 hours, now post-op taking 1.5 tabs Q4 hours. Part of medication reduction was due to afternoon lightheadedness. Better with lower Sinemet.  
6/30/22 pt is experiencing more apathy, recently and was advised to increase his carbi/levo IR 25/100 to 2 tabs, 5x/day.
1/24/23 pt's partner says that she cannot understand most of what he says. She also feels that the second DBS surgery (R-GPI) has been more negative than positive. She feels that he also took a "cognitive hit" after second side.

column85:
5/3/22 given bothersome motor symptoms, pt started Rytary in 2016, which has been very helpful with left hand dexterity. In 2019, Rytary dose was increased and entacapone was added.
8/17/22 pt self-weaned himself off multiple medications, including Rytary, Amantadine and Rasagiline. However, he then noticed more difficulty with typing, speech and left arm tremor, which improved since restarting Rytary. Rytary doses are lasting longer than pre-DBS - he now has difficulty remembering to take doses on time. 
3/14/23 trials for best medication regiment revealed that LESS Rytary was much better. Rytary 145mg QID was too low (more tremor).

column85:
6/29/22 pt has been able to drastically reduce his medication.
7/21/22 pt  likely needs a 4th dose of Rytary or Sinemet 25/100 but wife is concerned about his prior reaction to high doses of dopamine (levodopa-induced psychosis.)  She was reassured that he has reduced his meds over 50% and is now on very low doses and his PD symptoms may be under better control with slightly higher doses. 
11/23/22  pt has end of day ‘over medicated’ state with rapid speech which may be secondary to stacking effect of Rytary 95 QID.  He wears off after the 4th dose in late afternoon, but they are concerned about taking a 5th dose of Rytary that will affect his cognitive and mood state. 
1/11/23 pt  has explored taking a 1/4 or 1/2 tabs of Sinemet at different times a day - sometimes this has been helpful to have more reliable on time but this has not worked as well after he had a dentist appointment.
3/8/23 pt started Dhivy 2 days ago to try this new formulation instead of the regular Sinemet.

Using later postop T1 imaging due to pt having an aneurysm + headache & head trauma. 
Postop CT imaging 7/10/22 (Ax. 10022227439); havent downloaded to imaging database; has 'bone recon' postop CT.
column84:
In ON state pt did not feel completely ON, though had mild facial dyskinesias.
Virtual visit.
column85:
3/3/21 pt generally holds 6pm dose of Amantadine if hallucinations recur.
6/9/21 neurologist recommended that the pt cut out the extra Sinemet IR tabs and just continue with the Stalevo.
6/30/21 pt's mood is much better since coming off Amantadine.
12/15/21 per pt preference, he transitioned from Stalevo five times a day to Rytary 145 mg 3 capsules three times a day. 
2/2/22 all pt's  symptoms have improved somewhat on the new Rytary dose.
5/4/22 pt  is probably a little better on the four times per day dosing of Rytary, but is still getting peak dose dyskinesias.
1/25/23 pt is taking a Sinemet IR booster about 1-2 per day and this is when he gets the toe curling, which is a sign that he is starting to wear off. By taking the extra Sinemet IR at this time - he can avoid the anxiety attacks.

Postop CT imaging 7/10/22 (Ax. 10022227439); havent downloaded to imaging database; has 'bone recon' postop CT.
column84:
In ON state pt did not feel completely ON, though had mild facial dyskinesias.
Virtual visit.
column85:
3/3/21 pt generally holds 6pm dose of Amantadine if hallucinations recur.
6/9/21 neurologist recommended that the pt cut out the extra Sinemet IR tabs and just continue with the Stalevo.
6/30/21 pt's mood is much better since coming off Amantadine.
12/15/21 per pt preference, he transitioned from Stalevo five times a day to Rytary 145 mg 3 capsules three times a day. 
2/2/22 all pt's  symptoms have improved somewhat on the new Rytary dose.
5/4/22 pt  is probably a little better on the four times per day dosing of Rytary, but is still getting peak dose dyskinesias.
1/25/23 pt is taking a Sinemet IR booster about 1-2 per day and this is when he gets the toe curling, which is a sign that he is starting to wear off. By taking the extra Sinemet IR at this time - he can avoid the anxiety attacks.

column85:
5/19/21 pt developed dyskinesias of the left hemi body which rapidly improved with reduction of his Sinemet.
6/25/21 pt increased his medications - back up to 2 tabs in the morning and 1.5 tabs for the other doses. This improved his movements significantly. He does feel sometimes with exercise that he needs a full 2 tabs and so will take an extra tab on those occasions. 
7/14/21 pt had Ropinirole 2mg added to his chart, but no doses were added and therefore not in LEDD score. 
2/23/22 pt stopped the Rotigotine (mainly due to cost).
8/17/22 pt has started taking Pramipexole 0.125mg TID as prescribed with no noticeable difference.
